post_text:
September 3, 2020

Dear Parent or Guardian,

In an ongoing effort to continuously improve upon its practices, Fort Payne High School invites parents of our students to take part in its annual survey. This year FPHS will use the AdvancED Parent Survey to capture parents’ input, and help target areas of improvement and effectiveness within the school. The AdvancED Parent Survey is also a requirement for accreditation by AdvancED.

The AdvancED Parent Survey gives parents the opportunity to provide their input, opinions and feedback about the school. The results are used to guide FPHS administrators and faculty members in future improvements and organizational efforts to help our students, parents, and community.

We value your opinion and ask that you take the time to complete this survey. Please go to https://eprovesurveys.advanc-ed.org/surveys/#/action/140023/22612 to complete the survey. Your response to this survey will be anonymous. Your honest opinion is appreciated.

Thank you for your time,

Steve D. Sparks
Fort Payne High School
Assistant Principal

post_text:
Announcement!

Fort Payne City Schools would like to announce that beginning today, September 4, all students enrolled in our school system will be eligible to eat breakfast and lunch free until December 31, 2020 due to the passage of a USDA waiver.

If you usually submit a free/reduced price application, please go ahead and turn in a form to the child nutrition office. The amount of federal funding our entire school system receives is based on the percentage of our students receiving free and reduced-price meals.

If you usually submit a free/reduced price application, please go ahead and turn in a form to the child nutrition office. The amount of federal funding our entire school system receives is based on the percentage of our students receiving free and reduced-price meals.

post_text:
NEW TICKET POLICY: Card & Mobile Payment Only
Beginning for the 2020-21 school year, Fort Payne High School will begin implementing a Card & Mobile Payment Only ticketing policy at all athletic events. Fans will be able to purchase tickets online through Fort Payne’s GoFan page or by presenting a debit/credit card (or mobile payment option) at the ticket gate.
The new ticketing policy allows Fort Payne to operate a more efficient and professional ticket gate, while creating an enhanced fan experience. Purchasing tickets online allows fans to easily access and share tickets (email or text) without standing in line.
A new ticket gate setup will help promote social distancing, while limiting person-to-person contact and the physical exchange of cash.
Fans are encouraged to purchase their tickets online prior to reaching the facility. For your convenience, signage will be setup at the venue to allow fans to easily navigate an online purchase. Debit/Credit card stations will be setup to support card and mobile payment options at the ticket gates.
https://gofan.co/app/school/AL816

Bruce's Foodland of Fort Payne Donated cases of bags for food distribution-Thank You!
Taco Bell of Fort Payne donated bags for food distribution-Thank you!
Roadside Que of Fort Payne provided food for our volunteers-Thank you, Justin and Greg!
Blue Jug of Fort Payne provided food for our volunteers-Thank you, Sarah!

If we've left anyone out, please let us know! More importantly, do what you can to help, and thank others who are helping. What a great community we live in!

post_text:
Dear Students and Parents of Fort Payne City Schools,

I hope all of you are well and practicing social distancing. As you are probably aware Governor Ivey has closed Public Schools for the remainder of the school year. We will now move to virtual school and paper packets for the rest of the school year beginning Monday, April 6, 2020. We will be sending iPads home for all K-4 students, which will allow virtual instruction K-12. I will be sending out more information next week and you will be contacted by your teachers no later than April 6, 2020. We will continue to make meals available for the remainder of the school year. Our CNP Staff and volunteers have done an amazing job the past two weeks providing meals for our students. We will finalize our lesson delivery next week and I will reach out with more information. I want to assure you that we will do our best to make this a productive academic experience.

Please be as safe as possible during this health emergency.

Jim Cunningham, Superintendent
Fort Payne City Schools

post_text:
Mrs. Neta DiNardi Will Be Retiring - After 42 Years in the Fort Payne City School System!

Mrs. DiNardi began her career in the Fort Payne City School System in 1977 working in the WAES cafeteria preparing meals for the students. She was there until 1988 when she transitioned to the position of FPMS Cafeteria Manager. In 1993 she moved into the FPMS School Secretary position and has been there ever since. She has worked under 7 different principals during her 42 years with Fort Payne City Schools and has seen many changes. After decades of calling students to the office to checkout, it is finally her turn. We all wish her the BEST! Enjoy your retirement...We will miss you!
Please LIKE to show your appreciation for Mrs. DiNardi's many years of service.

post_text:
The FPMS robotics teams competed at the state FIRST LEGO League Championship on 3/2. Here are the Results:
-The Short Circuits team won the 1st Inspiration award.
-The High Voltage team finished 4th place in the robot game and won 1st place Research.
-Gigawatts won 2nd place overall. The Gigawatts also won the Global Innovation Award for their Astrofit suit. This is the second year in a row the team has won this honor.

The Global Innovation winner now has a chance to compete nationally for $25,000 that is used to help develop their product. In addition, the Gigawatts and High Voltage teams received invitations to compete at the international level. They both will attend the Razorback Invitational at the University of Arkansas this May.

post_text:
LaGrange College Greenpower Race
The high school and middle school Greenpower teams competed Saturday (2/23) in Lagrange, GA for the Diversepower Grand Prix. Over 30 race cars were in attendance. The high school team finished 3rd in the pit crew challenge, but had a relay burn up to put them out of the race early. The middle school suffered a flat tire and melted wire, but still managed to finish 9th. They also won 2nd place in presentation and 2nd place in the pit crew challenge.

FPMS Student Recognized by Governor Kay Ivey:
Anna Banks, Alabama's Southern Miss Teen, and current 8th grade student at Fort Payne Middle School was recognized by Governor Kay Ivey on Wednesday, February 27th at the State Capitol building. Anna was recognized for her exemplary character, hours of community service and for being such a great role model for our younger generation with her “Think Before You Speak” program. Anna created this program to promote kindness and with the goal to erase bullying.

Thank you in advance for your help with this worthy cause!

post_text:
The Fort Payne Middle School Robotics teams pass on to the FIRST Lego League State Championship on March 2, 2019.
1) The 5th grade team, High Voltage, won the Core Values award at their Qualifier this past weekend. This was their first time competing.
2) The Short Circuits took home the highest award by winning the overall Qualifier championship and will pass on to state as well.
3) In a previous Qualifier, the Gigawatts won the Project award and passed to state as well.
4) For the fourth year in a row Fort Payne will have multiple teams representing at the FIRST Lego State Championship.

Congratulations on a well-played football game last Friday. We wanted to let you know that WAFF 48 has selected a Fort Payne play as a finalist for our weekly ‘Play Of The Week’ fan-voting segment.

Fort Payne is up against plays from Athens and Hartselle this week. You can read the official rules, see the plays, and cast your vote right now at: www.waff.com/playoftheweek/

Voting will close at Noon, Wednesday, September 19. The winning school will be announced on WAFF 48 News at 6pm Wednesday and on Facebook at www.facebook.com/fridaynightfever.

The winning school will be presented with their $500 prize on Thursday.

YOUR SUPPORT IS GREATLY APPRECIATED!

On behalf of the Fort Payne City School Board, the Fort Payne City School Employees, and the Students of Fort Payne, I would like to thank you for your continued support of our school system. The renewal of the school taxes on June 5, 2018, will provide the continued support needed to continue our current level of educational opportunities. The approval rate for this tax renewal was outstanding! Your pride and confidence in our school system was evident by the tremendous support displayed. Again, we truly appreciate the value you place on public education in our community.
Jim Cunningham, Superintendent
Fort Payne City Schools

A Message from Mr. Jim Cunningham, FPCS Superintendent:

Please VOTE FOR the renewal of current school taxes on June 5th! We must have the sustained support of our communities in order to meet our current educational costs.
THESE ARE NOT NEW TAXES, but the continuation of the current taxes that have been in place for decades.
Please make sure to vote for the renewal of these school taxes.

post_text: The Fort Payne Middle School STEAM Competition recently competed at the Alabama Conference of Theatre Competition in Montgomery. Fort Payne competed against schools from across the state in solo and duet acting as well as musicals. All students from Fort Payne received Exemplary status on their judges’ scores. This is the highest rating you can receive. In addition, Kendall Binkley and Chloe Goggans won 3rd place in Duet Acting (4-5 Grade)

FPHS Prom "Light Up the Night" is Saturday (4/7/18) at the Dekalb Theater in Downtown Fort Payne from 7:00 - 11:00.
FPHS students have had prom activities all week to include reminders on being safe prom night!

Due to inclement weather conditions for this afternoon (3/19 - http://whnt.com/weather/forecast/), there will be NO after-school activities at Fort Payne City Schools.
Fort Payne City Schools will be in session during normal hours today, but there will be NO after-school activities. This would include EDP and sports. Stay safe and keep up with the forecast.

post_text:
Fort Payne Weight Team are State Champions!
Our boys and girls both got Overall State Champions at the AHSAA State Weight Meet.
WAES students Patrick Buffington 3rd grade and Jon Parker Buffington 4th grade also represented with wins: Patrick placed 3rd in the 98lb weight class and Jon Parker placed 1st 105lb weight class.

UPCOMING FRESHMEN ORIENTATION for ALL CURRENT 8th GRADERS and OPEN HOUSE for CURRENT FPHS STUDENTS!!! (Monday, March 12th)

AGENDA:
4:30 – 5:00 - Chromebook Fees Collection in Gym Lobby for upcoming Freshmen($40 or $20 for free/reduced lunch students)
5:00 – 5:30 - A word from the principal, Mr. Brian Jett, for upcoming Freshmen. (Parents and students should sit in the bleachers).
5:30 - 6:00 – Upcoming Freshmen will report to assigned homeroom teachers for homeroom teacher introductions.
--There will be presentations from students in the Teaching Careers.
--Students will turn in registration forms.
6:00 – 7:00 – Campus tours for upcoming Freshmen and their families/Meetings with teachers for current FPHS students

post_text:
FAFSA Help for SENIOR PARENTS of FPHS STUDENTS:

Someone will be available in the FPHS Library Monday night, March 12, to help with FAFSA application completion or to answer questions.
Call the high school office at 256-845-0535 to sign up for a time slot, either from 5:00 to 6:00 or from 6:00 to 7:00.
There are only a few slots available in each time frame!
https://fafsa.ed.gov/
